content.value: Catawba Nation's Cultural Division is tasked with "protecting, preserving, promoting, and maintaining the rich cultural heritage of the Catawba Nation." Since our original incorporation in 1989 as the Catawba Cultural Preservation Project we have accomplished that mission through a number of projects and initiatives.
The Trading Post is the world's largest buyer and seller of Catawba pottery, art, and other objects. All proceeds go to support our programs.

We hold the only professional archival collection in the world solely dedicated to Catawba history and material culture. In addition to our physical space, which is available by appointment to the Catawba community as well as outside scholars, we host a Digital Archives where members of the community can view our collection online.
The heart of our work is ensuring the preservation and growth of our traditions through community classes. These regular classes include pottery, foraging, basketry, history, and much more.

The Catawba Library is part of the Community Resource Center and provides digital and physical resources to the Catawba community. Our collection includes books, databases, films, audio-books, and more.

Since its inception one of our core programs has been teaching the non-Catawba public about our culture and history. Over the years our programs have grown beyond drumming and demonstrations to include history, traditional stories, language, trail walks, and even food!

In addition to our community language classes and work with various Catawba programs, we also offer the Catawba Language App free of charge. Use the app to learn new words, practice phrases, hear pronunciation, and type words in Catawba.
The National Historic Preservation Act (NHPA) was amended in 1996 giving Federally Recognized tribes formal responsibility for the preservation of significant historic properties on tribal lands.

In the early 1990's the Cultural Center found its permanent home in the former Catawba School House thanks to a donation of the building from the local Church of Latter Day Saints. We welcome guests to visit our historic building, exhibitions, and trails.

The Catawba Cultural Center is supported in part by an American Rescue Plan Act grant from the National Endowment for the Arts to support general operating expenses in response to the COVID-19 pandemic.

Catawba Nation's library is here to provide resources, digital support, books, films, databases, and other kinds of media to the Catawba Nation community. Since time immemorial Catawbas have valued stories and information which today can take many forms. Like many libraries we support our community members through database access, library rentals, space for study or work, etc. Unlike other libraries we prioritize media created by and about Catawbas, Native peoples, and other topics of interest to the Catawba Nation.

The National Historic Preservation Act (NHPA) was amended in 1996. Federally recognized tribes were given formal responsibility for the preservation of significant historic properties on tribal lands through the work of established tribal historic preservation programs. THPOs assume any and all of the functions of a State Historic Preservation Officer (SHPO) on their tribal lands. There are over 200 THPOs to date. The role of THPOs in the Section 106 process includes, but is not limited to, consultations regarding culturally appropriate methods for the following: Identification of historic properties of religious and cultural significance. Evaluation of such properties for eligibility of the National Register of Historic Places. Assessment of effects to historic properties. Determination of appropriate means to avoid, minimize, or mitigate adverse effects to such properties. Resolution of adverse effects.

Section 106 of the NHPA requires federal agencies to consider the effects of projects they carry out, license, or financially assist (undertakings) on historic properties and to provide
the ACHP an opportunity to comment on such undertakings. This means that Tribes have the right to be consulted on any Federal project that is on their Ancestral lands in addition to their tribal lands.

fields.question: In what area does Catawba THPO provide consultations and reviews?

content.value: Per Section 106  of the NHPA we provide consultations and reviews on our tribally-controlled lands, such as our two reservations in South Carolina, and throughout our ancestral homelands. Our areas of interest include the entirety of South Carolina and North Carolina as well as locations in Georgia, Virginia, West Virginia, Tennessee, and Pennsylvania. These areas of interest may grow or change due to further research.

fields.question: Why do tribes in one state have a right to comment on Federal projects in another state?

content.value: Our relationship to various places preceded the creation of state boundaries and because Section 106 of NHPA applies to Federal projects and projects requiring Federal licensing.

In 1848, just as the University completed two other residence halls, the Columbia Daily Telegraph suggested (in writing?) that the University rename its buildings for prominent South Carolina citizens and alumni. This is how this building, originally named "New South", came to bear the name of Founding Father, Governor, Diplomat to Spain, and former US Representative Charles Pinckney, Jr. A cursory look at his biography doesn't reveal any obvious connections to tribal nations - he never negotiated a treaty with a tribe, for example - but like other politicians of his time he could not avoid creating policies and formulating opinions about the United States' relationship with tribes.

Charles Pinckney was born and raised in a wealthy Charleston family where he studied law and eventually joined the Charles Towne Militia to defend the city against the British during the Revolutionary War. As the War came to a close, Pinckney once again turned his eye towards national and international politics. In December 1784, Pinckney wrote about his various policy opinions including his belief that Americans should traverse the Mississippi River regardless of Spain's opinions (he didn't comment on the wishes of the Mississippi River tribes) and the increasing importance of negotiating peace treaties with tribal nations in the South and West. It's important to remember that Pinckney was not referring to what we think of as the American West today. He was referring to something much closer: the Appalachian Mountains extending to the Mississippi River. Over time where "the West" is has moved.

By 1784, he was appointed as a South Carolina delegate to the ongoing federal negotiations over the new constitution. During the final Constitutional Convention, he proposed his own constitution draft. Unfortunately the version he presented has been lost to history but a reconstructed draft highlights some of the politics he would champion for the rest of his life: religious freedom and separation of church and state, a strong federal government and the prohibition of state-negotiated treaties, and the continued enslavement of people.

Following his return to South Carolina, Pinckney was elected Governor where he remained for nearly a decade. Following the election of Thomas Jefferson, whom Pickney campaigned for in South Carolina, Pinckney was selected as the Diplomat to Spain where he unsuccessfully tried to ....
-Spain & Earlier letter: what about the tribes? Appeasement over negotiation
-Louisiana Purchase: got Spain to acquiesce, talk about the LP

When Andrew Jackson was born in 1767, Catawbas and other Native peoples had lived on these lands for more than 6 millennia. While historians debate the exact location of Jackson’s birth, it was almost certainly on Catawba lands - lands that would have only become available to Jackson’s parents through treaties made between the British Crown and Catawba Nation, such as the Treaty of Augusta in 1763 that created the unique right-angled border between Charlotte, NC and York County, NC.

Andrew Jackson’s legacy is a site for debate, but certain facts remain: Jackson was the child of immigrants from Ulster, Ireland who settled in what was the British colonial frontier. Jackson moved to the small frontier town of Nashville, TN following the revolutionary war where he prospered through illegal speculation on Cherokee and Chickasaw treaty lands and the enslavement of people, Jackson rose to national prominence following the war of 1812 when he organized a militia to mount a campaign to crush Mvscogee resistance to continued encroachment on their lands. Jackson became president and is today remembered by many for one piece of legislation he signed into law: the Indian Removal Act of 1830 which created a framework for the taking and forced migration of tribes.

Jackson is synonymous with Indian Removal today and with good reason - he was so adamant on forcing the removal of tribes that he even ignored the decision of the Supreme Court. But Jackson was hardly the first or only president to make use of forced removals. Washington ordered General Sullivan to destroy more than 40 Haudenosaunee villages causing a massive and catastrophic exodus of Haudenosaunee people from what we now call New York State. Abraham Lincoln presided over the Long Walk in the 1860’s where thousands of Dine (Navajo) people were forcibly marched hundreds of miles to an internment camp.

This piece - “Unshadowed Land” - by Nicholas Galanin (Tlingit) asks the question: what do we do with this history? In collaboration with Catawba Nation, the Davidson community has excavated this lawn in the shape of an Andrew Jackson statue in Lafayette Square in Washington, DC. In the Spring of 2022 this shape will be filled in with soil and planted with Catawba corn - a variety of corn developed by Catawbas for thousands of years. In the Fall this corn will be harvested and returned to Catawba Nation. It is our hope that this project and land will be a step towards reweaving Catawba Nation and the Davidson community.

When Andrew Jackson was born in 1767, Catawbas and other Native peoples had lived on these lands for more than 6 millennia. While historians debate the exact location of Jackson’s birth, it was almost certainly on Catawba lands - lands that would have only become available to Jackson’s parents through treaties made between the British Crown and Catawba Nation, such as the Treaty of Augusta in 1763 that created the unique right-angled border between Charlotte, NC and York County, NC.

Andrew Jackson’s legacy is a site for debate, but certain facts remain: Jackson was the child of immigrants from Ulster, Ireland who settled in what was the British colonial frontier. Jackson moved to the small frontier town of Nashville, TN following the revolutionary war where he prospered through illegal speculation on Cherokee and Chickasaw treaty lands and the enslavement of people, Jackson rose to national prominence following the war of 1812 when he organized a militia to mount a campaign to crush Mvscogee resistance to continued encroachment on their lands. Jackson became president and is today remembered by many for one piece of legislation he signed into law: the Indian Removal Act of 1830 which created a framework for the taking and forced migration of tribes.

Jackson is synonymous with Indian Removal today and with good reason - he was so adamant on forcing the removal of tribes that he even ignored the decision of the Supreme Court. But Jackson was hardly the first or only president to make use of forced removals. Washington ordered General Sullivan to destroy more than 40 Haudenosaunee villages causing a massive and catastrophic exodus of Haudenosaunee people from what we now call New York State. Abraham Lincoln presided over the Long Walk in the 1860’s where thousands of Dine (Navajo) people were forcibly marched hundreds of miles to an internment camp.

This piece - “Unshadowed Land” - by Nicholas Galanin (Tlingit) asks the question: what do we do with this history? In the Fall this corn will be harvested and returned to Catawba Nation. It is our hope that this project and land will be a step towards reweaving Catawba Nation and the Davidson community.

As far as we know, no life has ever existed without water. We also know that almost all water on our planet is connected in a gigantic system. A drop of water in this creek - perhaps coming from the rain or welling up from a spring - will flow into the Catawba River. From there that drop may travel from the Catawba into the Wateree River, then the Santee River, and eventually the Atlantic Ocean.

That same drop may then travel more than 36,000 feet down to the deepest part of the ocean or travel the ocean currents around the globe. Eventually it may end up at the surface of the ocean where the sun’s warmth will transform the drop from a liquid to a gas. In its new lighter form, it will join millions of others to form clouds, traveling the world until it becomes too dense and
One day, many years into the future, that same drop that left this creek might someday return as a rainshower.
The health of this creek solely depends upon us humans to keep it clean and trash free so that it continues to be

Deep in these woods live the Yęhasuri (“The Little Wild People”). They look like miniature human beings described as having large teeth and live in the hollows of trees. And also described as being larger than fairies but smaller than leprechauns.  They spend a lot of their time hanging out around their fires and making music to lure nearby travelers deeper into the woods.

When the Yęhasuri get bored they will venture from their fires and creep under houses, where they will wait until they can reach up through the floorboards to pinch children. Sometimes, when they are feeling particularly mischievous they have been known to kidnap children. It has been told, they lured a young girl into the woods and tied her up to a tree by her hair and then rubbed harsh tobacco all over her arms and legs. Thankfully every child taken by the Yęhasuri eventually returned. As far as we know…
The Yęhasuri are one of the many reasons to stick to the trail path and to not wander off into the woods. Particularly if you hear the sound of small drums.

What is the fate of trees that have died? In front of you is a decomposing log. We are not sure how old this tree was when it died, but it was probably 50 years old at least. Life expectancy among trees varies greatly among species. To the west In the mountains of California, giant sequoias and bristlecone pines can live between three and five thousand years.

During this tree’s life, it was home to lots of other organisms like birds, mosses, and lichens that lived on it, but in general, a tree doesn’t like stuff living in it. In life, the tree’s bark prevented all sorts of organisms from growing inside of it. However, in death, the protection from the tree’s bark fades and detritivores, organisms that feed  on dead organic material, begin recycling the tree’s nutrients back into the forest.

The death of this particular tree gives new life to the forest. Decomposition is a continuous process and could last longer than the tree lived if not hundreds of years. As this log decomposes, new residents will make  their home. Plants and fungi will move in to take advantage of the log’s moisture and nutrient-rich organic material. Many different species of animals like insects, mites, slugs, and snails will also utilize this new resource for food and shelter. This slow process of decay and decomposition makes dead trees equally as important to forest health as their living counterparts.

Like all people, Catawbas have changed over time and adapted to new situations using ingenuity and creativity. Over the 6,000+ years that Catawbas have lived on these lands, there have been many approaches to building shelters, including roundhouses, longhouses, lean-tos, and more. In the 1700s and 1800s Catawba housing changed again as many Catawbas adopted cabin-style homes, like the one you see here.

Although the design of these structures came from the homes that nearby settlers were using, Catawbas brought their own knowledge of the land and its resources to construction. For example, you’ll notice red clay between the logs of this home, which provides excellent insulation from extreme temperatures, rain, wind, and pests. Catawbas likely also brought their knowledge of local trees to select the best wood for various components of the structure.

Around the world many cultures have developed the practice of burning medicinal and spiritual plants. The traditions are unique to each of thousands of cultures but the Native American tradition that most people are familiar with is the burning of White Sage which is also known as smudging. Cedar shavings and uncultured tobacco have been used in this region for smudging also. Sometimes a mixture of all three have been used by some native people.

White Sage does not naturally grow on Catawba lands because it prefers the well-drained, drier soils found on the western part of the continent. Instead, Catawbas have used other plants such as this beautiful Red Cedar. Also known as Eastern Juniper, this tree can be found throughout the East Coast and has many uses in addition to its beautiful aromatic smoke. For example, the cedar’s small, blue-berries can be dried, crushed, and used to season foods, like you use black pepper. The leaves and wood can also be used in roasting and grilling to add flavor to dishes.

This is an example of one traditional Catawba canoe design. Historically, Catawbas would make these dugouts by first finding a large, straight tree trunk, usually a Tulip Poplar. Once the bark was removed and the trunk was partially dried, Catawbas would set a fire on top of the log. Once the fire burned out, the burnt wood would be scraped away. This process would be repeated until there was an area large enough to seat one or more people. The sleek curves of this dugout were accomplished using carving tools.

Surviving isn’t just about growing the fastest or being the tallest. Ferns are ancient plants - they came about before plants even knew how to make seeds! Despite this, ferns have survived by remaining adaptable and by occupying a unique niche among plants.

Ferns rely on the dim, damp interior of forests, which is why they quickly die when left in the direct sunlight and why they often make excellent houseplants. In addition to their beauty, some ferns are edible. These are often called “fiddlehead ferns” because of the unique shape of their new leaves, which are curled inward like the head of a fiddle or violin.

Received knowledge dictates that ‘smooth fiddlehead ferns’ are edible but ‘hairy fiddlehead ferns’ can have negative health effects. As old growth forests diminished due to new settlements on Catawba lands, much of our traditional biodiversity disappeared. Today you are likely to only find the ‘hairy’ - and possibly toxic - variety of ferns in our woods.

Remember to never touch or eat a plant unless you have been trained and are absolutely certain about the plant you are eating. And remember that we ask visitors to Catawba Nation to not harvest along our trails.

This historic trail is part of a wagon wheel trail that dates back to 1810, likely used for trade and travel by both Catawba and settlers. During the 1800s and early 1900s, Catawbas established at least one ferry to carry wagons, people, and, eventually, cars across the Catawba River, making wagon trails essential for people intending to cross the river.

Today the trail connects with the Catawba River Greenway Trail and becomes part of the larger Carolina Thread Trail system of North and South Carolina. As you walk this gentle trail, you are treading land that has been home to the Catawba people for over 6,000 years, and at the end of your walk, you will be rewarded with an incredible view of the Catawba River, the spiritual heart of Catawba culture.

Sometimes we miss ‘the forest for the trees’ but more often we miss ‘the trees for the forest’. When we look at a forest like this one it’s easy to overlook the unique qualities of the trees that make it up. Every tree that you see in these woods is marked and changed by events that happened during its lifetime. Some of these impacts are invisible to us but others, such as a twisted tree trunk or a branch with a particular curve, are more apparent.
Trees adapt to the challenges and opportunities of life in many different ways, particularly depending on species. This tree,

, adapts by creating an incredibly dense and hard trunk. Traditionally this tree was valued by indigenous peoples - and later by settlers - as handles of tools and other high-impact uses which gives it the nickname “Iron Wood”. The trunk also has a unique tendency to grow thicker in some parts and thinner in other parts giving the appearance of something like a muscular arm or leg. This gives it another nickname - “Muscle Wood”.

There are many strategies to survive as a plant in the woods. Some trees grow quickly to avoid being shaded out by other plants. Some build strong trunks to keep them upright in storms and strong winds. Some stay small, using the meager sunlight as efficiently as possible. Others, like this grape vine, use a different strategy.

Muscadines, also known as wild grapes or Catawba grapes, take advantage of the sturdy trees around them by developing vines, similar to other plants such as Virginia Creeper and even Poison Ivy. Instead of investing energy and resources into building large trunks, these vines will use the trunks of other trees to reach sunlight at the top of the canopy. This allows them to grow more quickly than surrounding trees.

Muscadines, like other grapes, produce fruit  every year. The Muscadine produces only a few larger fruit instead of large clumps of smaller fruit, like the European grape. Muscadine fruits have thicker skins and a richer, muskier flavor than the typical grapes found at the grocery store. If you are wandering our trails in the late Summer or early Fall you might even stumble upon a Muscadine fruit.
The fruit of this particular Muscadine vine are likely high above us in the tops of the trees reserved as a special treat for squirrels, birds, insects, and other residents of the canopy.
, commonly known as eastern poison ivy or poison ivy, is an allergenic Asian and Eastern North American flowering plant in the genus

The species is well known for causing urushiol-induced contact dermatitis, an itchy, irritating, and sometimes painful rash, in most people who touch it. Urushiol is a clear liquid compound in the plant's sap.
The species is variable in its appearance and habit, and despite its common name, it is not a true ivy (genus
), but rather a member of the cashew and pistachio family (Anacardiaceae).

Poison ivy is commonly eaten by many animals, and the seeds are consumed by birds, but poison ivy is most often thought of as an unwelcome weed. So unwelcome that we have developed various mnemonic rhymes to help us identify it: “Leaves of three, let it be”, “Hairy vine, no friend of mine”, and “Berries white, run in fright”.

Native peoples have utilized other plants to alleviate rashes caused by poison ivy. Some of these include rubbing an infusion of Carolina horse nettle seeds onto the affected skin or soaking dried corn cobs in water and rubbing them on the rashed skin.

content.value: It’s hard to imagine when walking through woods like these that this area - commonly referred to as the Carolina Piedmont - wasn’t always heavily forested. When European colonizers first visited the Piedmont region, which lies between the Coastal Plain to the east and the Blue Ridge Mountains to the west, they would have seen something more like a savannah - a mixed woodland-grassland ecosystem characterized by trees being sufficiently spaced so that the canopy does not close. This open canopy allows sufficient light to reach the ground to support grasses and other non-woody vegetation such as forbs.

This “Piedmont Savannah”- which was abundant with deer and other large browsing mammals such as bison and elk - was created through the use of controlled burns by Catawbas and other native peoples in the area. As we and other tribes lost control of our lands, forests began to grow in place of savannahs since woody plant encroachment was no longer controlled by fire. This changing environment created new niches for plants to take advantage of. Two such plants are  the invasive Chinese Privet and Silverberry that you see along this section of trail. These plants were able to take advantage of the rapidly-changing ecosystem and have since become two of the most invasive plants in the region. Their fast growth, tolerance for poor soil, and ability to live in mixed-shade allows them to quickly outcompete other Native plants, such as River Cane. Catawba Nation is making efforts to control the spread of privet on our lands and reintroduce fire to the landscape.

, “The People of the River”. While archaeologists document examples of Catawba culture dating back more than 6,000 years, our stories tell us that we have always been here. Eventually, in the last 500 years, we became known as Catawba Nation and our river became known as the Catawba River.

Today we maintain our relationships with the River by sustaining our families through fishing, navigating the river in kayaks to honor our ancestors who navigated it by canoe, and by making our pottery which is only possible because of the clay rich banks of the Catawba River. It’s up to all of us to protect our river for current and future generations.

Wąsakį, or rivercane, is the tallest native grass in North America. The unpracticed eye might mistake it for bamboo since they are closely related. Although today it is increasingly difficult to find large, mature rivercane, the Southeast used to have canebreaks -areas dominated by rivercane - that stretched for miles. These ecosystems housed many unique species that depended on the rivercane ecosystem. One such animal, the Bachman’s Warbler, a small yellow and black bird, would travel from these cane breaks more than 1000 miles to Cuba and back every single year. In 2021, the US Fish and Wildlife Service recommended that the Bachman’s Warbler be declared extinct in large part due to the loss of rivercane habitat.

Catawbas and other tribes that had access to rivercane created many different uses for the plant including baskets and blow-guns. Due to long-standing cultural relationships with rivercane, Catawba Nation and other tribes have worked for many years to protect and revitalize the rivercane. Currently, Catawba Nation is exploring how to propagate rivercane, protect it from invasive species, and how it can be used to reduce erosion and environmental degradation.

, known in english as Tulip Poplar, is immediately recognizable in the Spring, Summer, and Fall due to its unique 4-lobed leaves. This plentiful tree grows quickly and to a large size, typically maintaining a very straight trunk, which makes it ideal for creating dugout canoes and other uses. Traditionally, Catawbas used the bark for the siding of buildings because of its water resistance and ability to remain as large, intact pieces.

Despite its English name, the tree is neither a tulip nor a poplar. It is a member of the Magnolia family making it closely related to the glossy-leaved magnolias characteristic of ornamental lawns of the Carolinas. The name “tulip poplar” is due to its vibrant yellow and orange flowers that resemble tulips.

Tulip poplars are a shade-intolerant species that are most commonly associated with the first century of forest succession. They are dominant species during the beginning of forest development but will be replaced by more shade-tolerant species as canopies close up and forests mature.

And also described as being larger than fairies but smaller than leprechauns.  They spend a lot of their time hanging out around their fires and making music to lure nearby travelers deeper into the woods.

When the Yęhasuri get bored they will venture from their fires and creep under houses, where they will wait until they can reach up through the floorboards to pinch children. Sometimes, when they are feeling particularly mischievous they have been known to kidnap children. It has been told, they lured a young girl into the woods and tied her up to a tree by her hair and then rubbed harsh tobacco all over her arms and legs. Thankfully every child taken by the Yęhasuri eventually returned. As far as we know…
The Yęhasuri are one of the many reasons to stick to the trail path and to not wander off into the woods. Particularly if you hear the sound of small drums.
Throughout this part of the trail you might notice a few unique, but familiar, plants:

also known as ‘Adam’s Needle’ or locally as simply ‘yucca’. These pointy plants stand out against the forest, like something that was transported from the tropics or the desert. In reality, the relatives of this plant can be found in ecosystems across the Americas from the rainforests of the Caribbean and Central America to the arid, rocky Southwest, all the way into frigid climates farther north. Today they are frequently used in gardens and landscaping.

These unique plants have some unexpected uses. Firstly, the white, bell-shaped flowers are edible and can be used like squash blossoms or any leafy green. Secondly, the leaves can be turned into a strong fiber. A rope made from this fiber is called cordage and is strong enough that it was even used to hold beams together in traditional Catawba round houses.

In the 1700s and 1800s Catawba housing changed again as many Catawbas adopted cabin-style homes, like the one you see here.

Although the design of these structures came from the homes that nearby settlers were using, Catawbas brought their own knowledge of the land and its resources to construction. For example, you’ll notice red clay between the logs of this home, which provides excellent insulation from extreme temperatures, rain, wind, and pests. Catawbas likely also brought their knowledge of local trees to select the best wood for various components of the structure.

Around the world many cultures have developed the practice of burning medicinal and spiritual plants. The traditions are unique to each of thousands of cultures but the Native American tradition that most people are familiar with is the burning of White Sage which is also known as smudging. Cedar shavings and uncultured tobacco have been used in this region for smudging also. Sometimes a mixture of all three have been used by some native people.

White Sage does not naturally grow on Catawba lands because it prefers the well-drained, drier soils found on the western part of the continent. Instead, Catawbas have used other plants such as this beautiful Red Cedar. Also known as Eastern Juniper, this tree can be found throughout the East Coast and has many uses in addition to its beautiful aromatic smoke. For example, the cedar’s small, blue-berries can be dried, crushed, and used to season foods, like you use black pepper. The leaves and wood can also be used in roasting and grilling to add flavor to dishes.
